Below are Qutes implementations for the Deutsch–Jozsa algorithm and quantum teleportation, using only language features documented in the corpus.

## Deutsch–Jozsa in Qutes

The algorithm decides whether a binary function is **constant** or **balanced**. In Qutes this means preparing the input register in superposition, applying the oracle, applying a second Hadamard layer, and measuring the input register. If any measured input qubit is `1`, the function is balanced; otherwise it is constant.

```qutes
qubit[] input = [|0>, |0>, |0>];
qubit output = |->;

void oracle(qubit[] _input, qubit _output){
    foreach qubit q in _input {
        mcx q, _output;
    }
}

// First Hadamard layer: put input register in superposition.
foreach qubit q in input {
    hadamard q;
}

// Apply the oracle.
oracle(input, output);

// Second Hadamard layer: interfere the superposition.
foreach qubit q in input {
    hadamard q;
}

// Measure the input register via implicit measurement on assignment to bool.
bool result;
bool found_one = false;
foreach qubit q in input {
    result = q;
    if(result){
        found_one = true;
    }
}

if(found_one){
    print "Balanced";
}
else{
    print "Constant";
}
```

## Quantum teleportation in Qutes

Teleportation moves an unknown qubit from Alice to Bob using a shared Bell pair, a Bell measurement by Alice, two classical bits, and corrective Pauli gates by Bob. The corpus shows the outline but does not define `aliceEncoding` and `bobDecoding`; here they are written using only documented gates.

```qutes
void entangle(qubit a, qubit b) {
    hadamard a;
    mcx a, b;
}

void aliceEncoding(qubit msg, qubit half) {
    mcx msg, half;
    hadamard msg;
}

void bobDecoding(qubit target, bool do_z, bool do_x) {
    if(do_z){
        pauliz target;
    }
    if(do_x){
        not target;
    }
}

// Alice and Bob share a Bell pair.
qubit bellA = 0q;
qubit bellB = 0q;
entangle(bellA, bellB);

// The qubit Alice wants to teleport.
qubit message = 1q;

// Alice entangles her qubit with her half and measures.
aliceEncoding(message, bellA);
bool do_z = message;
bool do_x = bellA;

// Bob applies the corrections and obtains the teleported state.
bobDecoding(bellB, do_z, do_x);
print bellB;
```

### Notes on corpus availability

- The published teleportation snippet references `aliceEncoding` and `bobDecoding` but does not provide their bodies; the version above defines them with `mcx`, `hadamard`, `pauliz`, and `not`.
- Qutes has no documented dedicated Bell-measurement gate, so the measurement is decomposed into `mcx`, `hadamard`, and assignment to `bool`.
- The lexer examples list `pauliy` and `pauliz` but not `paulix`; the `not` gate performs the same Pauli-X correction used by Bob.
- `print bellB;` relies on Qutes' implicit measurement behavior when a quantum variable is printed.

